ntsync 1012: snapshot e fields under obj_lock in CHANNEL_RECV / RECV2

Cross-thread slab-use-after-free in ntsync_channel_recv (and the
near-duplicate ntsync_channel_recv2) caught by KASAN under
test-mixed-load-stress 2026-05-04:

  BUG: KASAN: slab-use-after-free in ntsync_obj_ioctl+0x4e88/0x5ac0
  Read of size 4 at addr ffff8882f2b2d638 by task test-mixed-load/29803
  ...
  Allocated by task 29798: ntsync_obj_ioctl+0x20c8 (kzalloc in SEND_PI)
  Freed     by task 29798: ntsync_obj_ioctl+0x3e28 (kfree in SEND_PI cleanup)

Race shape:

  T-A (SEND_PI):                    T-B (RECV / RECV2):
    kzalloc(e), refcount=1
    obj_lock; insert e; obj_unlock
    wait_event_interruptible (parks
        on e->wq waiting e->replied)
                                    obj_lock
                                    e = pop pending
                                    e->state = DISPATCHED
                                    list_add_tail(&e->list, dispatched)
                                    depth--
                                    obj_unlock                <-- RACE OPEN
    SIGUSR1 arrives (test shutdown
        calls pthread_kill on the
        sender);  wait wakes via
        signal_pending; ret =
        -ERESTARTSYS
    obj_lock
    state == DISPATCHED:
        list_del(&e->list)
    obj_unlock
    refcount_dec_and_test → 0
    kfree(e)                        apply_event_pi_boost(... e->policy,
                                                        e->prio, ...)  ← UAF
                                    args.* = e->id ... e->prio          ← UAF

The 1009 refcount fix coordinated SEND_PI sleeper vs. REPLY's
wake_up_all so REPLY's late wq access stays valid.  It did not cover
the receiver, which never takes a refcount on e — the receiver pops
e and then reads e->fields outside obj_lock.  When the sender is
interrupted in this window the sender frees e before the receiver
finishes reading.

Fix: snapshot every field the receiver reads (entry_id, payload_off,
reply_off, sender_tid, prio for both RECV and RECV2; thread_token in
RECV2; policy + prio for the boost call) into local variables BEFORE
dropping obj_lock.  After unlock the receiver only touches the
snapshots — never e — so the sender's free is harmless.

Chosen over taking a refcount on the receiver because:
  - snapshot adds ~7 cache-hot struct loads (e was just touched by
    pop + list_add_tail) on the gamma audio dispatcher's hot path
  - refcount_inc + refcount_dec_and_test would add 2 atomics per RECV
    forever; the dispatcher runs at audio rate, this matters
  - snapshot is the smaller diff and matches NSPA's existing pattern
    of preferring local-stack snapshots over per-call-site refcounts
    when the pointer doesn't escape the function

apply_event_pi_boost continues to run outside obj_lock (it can sleep
under PREEMPT_RT) — it just operates on the snapshotted policy/prio
values now.

Signed-off-by: NSPA-Claude <claude@nspa.local>
--- a/drivers/misc/ntsync.c	2026-04-30 21:05:58.851093317 -0500
+++ b/drivers/misc/ntsync.c	2026-05-04 20:50:33.116062909 -0500
@@ -1740,21 +1740,37 @@
 	e->state = NTSYNC_CH_DISPATCHED;
 	list_add_tail(&e->list, &ch->u.channel.dispatched);
 	ch->u.channel.depth--;
-	obj_unlock(ch);
-
-	/* Auto-boost: lift us to the popped entry's priority for the
-	 * handler duration.  Released at next RECV (drain at top). */
-	if (e->prio) {
-		if (apply_event_pi_boost(ch->dev, current,
-					 e->policy, e->prio, new_ep))
-			new_ep = NULL;
-	}
 
+	/* NSPA 1012: snapshot e's fields BEFORE dropping obj_lock.  After
+	 * unlock the SEND_PI sleeper can be interrupted (signal_pending),
+	 * detach itself via list_del under obj_lock, drop its refcount and
+	 * kfree(e) — all before we get back to read e->prio / e->id below.
+	 * The receiver doesn't hold a refcount on e, so any read of e after
+	 * obj_unlock is a slab-UAF window.  The KASAN finding 2026-05-04
+	 * (test-mixed-load-stress, T29798 sender alloc+free, T29803 recv
+	 * read at e->prio) hit exactly this race during signal-driven test
+	 * shutdown.  Mirror fix in ntsync_channel_recv2 below. */
 	args.entry_id    = e->id;
 	args.payload_off = e->payload_off;
 	args.reply_off   = e->reply_off;
 	args.sender_tid  = e->sender_tid;
 	args.prio        = e->prio;
+	{
+		/* apply_event_pi_boost may sleep under PREEMPT_RT, so it must
+		 * run outside obj_lock.  Snapshot the boost params first. */
+		__u32 boost_policy = e->policy;
+		__u32 boost_prio   = e->prio;
+		obj_unlock(ch);
+
+		/* Auto-boost: lift us to the popped entry's priority for the
+		 * handler duration.  Released at next RECV (drain at top). */
+		if (boost_prio) {
+			if (apply_event_pi_boost(ch->dev, current,
+						 boost_policy, boost_prio, new_ep))
+				new_ep = NULL;
+		}
+	}
+
 	if (copy_to_user(argp, &args, sizeof(args)))
 		ret = -EFAULT;
 
@@ -1820,20 +1836,28 @@
 	 * a thread that died and deregistered between SEND_PI and RECV2
 	 * yields token=0 → userspace fallback to get_thread_from_id. */
 	e->thread_token = channel_lookup_token(ch, e->sender_tid);
-	obj_unlock(ch);
-
-	if (e->prio) {
-		if (apply_event_pi_boost(ch->dev, current,
-					 e->policy, e->prio, new_ep))
-			new_ep = NULL;
-	}
 
+	/* NSPA 1012: snapshot e's fields BEFORE obj_unlock — see commentary
+	 * in ntsync_channel_recv above.  Same SEND_PI-cleanup-vs-receiver
+	 * race window applies here. */
 	args.entry_id     = e->id;
 	args.payload_off  = e->payload_off;
 	args.reply_off    = e->reply_off;
 	args.sender_tid   = e->sender_tid;
 	args.prio         = e->prio;
 	args.thread_token = e->thread_token;
+	{
+		__u32 boost_policy = e->policy;
+		__u32 boost_prio   = e->prio;
+		obj_unlock(ch);
+
+		if (boost_prio) {
+			if (apply_event_pi_boost(ch->dev, current,
+						 boost_policy, boost_prio, new_ep))
+				new_ep = NULL;
+		}
+	}
+
 	if (copy_to_user(argp, &args, sizeof(args)))
 		ret = -EFAULT;
 
